# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bay-leaf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bay-leaf/aframomum-corrorima] The spice, known as **Ethiopian cardamom**, **false cardamom**, or ***korarima***, is obtained from the plant's seeds (usually dried), and is extensively used in Ethiopian and Eritrean cuisine.
[src:bay-leaf/aframomum-corrorima] It is an ingredient in *berbere*, *mitmita*, *awaze*, and other spice mixtures, and is also used to flavor coffee.
[src:bay-leaf/aframomum-corrorima] Its flavor is comparable to that of the closely related *Elettaria cardamomum* or green cardamom.
[src:bay-leaf/aframomum-corrorima] In Ethiopian herbal medicine, the seeds are used as a tonic, carminative, and laxative.
[src:bay-leaf/aframomum-corrorima] The plant is native to Tanzania, western Ethiopia (in the vicinity of Lake Tana and Gelemso), southwestern Sudan, western Uganda.
[src:bay-leaf/aframomum-corrorima] It is cultivated in both Ethiopia and Eritrea, although the fruits are typically harvested from wild plants.
[src:bay-leaf/aframomum-corrorima] The dried fruits are widely sold in markets and are relatively expensive, while fresh fruits are sold in production areas.
[src:bay-leaf/aframomum-corrorima] In dried seeds and pods, the major oil components are 1,8-cineole (eucalyptol) and (E)-nerolidol.
[src:bay-leaf/aframomum-corrorima] In fresh seeds, the major component of the essential oil is 1,8-cineole, followed by sabinene and geraniol.
[src:bay-leaf/aframomum-corrorima] In fresh pods, the major oil constituents are *γ*-terpinene, *β*-pinene, *α*-phellandrene, 1,8-cineole, and *p*-cymene.
[src:bay-leaf/ajika] The dish is also prepared in Sakarya, Turkey among the Abaza people and is patented by the Turkish Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:bay-leaf/ajika] In 2018, ajika was included on the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Georgia list.
[src:bay-leaf/ajika] The word *ajika* comes from the Abkhaz language and means 'salt'.
[src:bay-leaf/ajika] However, in the Mingrelian language, a sharp linguistic distinction is maintained: the native word for salt is **jim** (ჯიმჷ), while *ajika* (აჯიკა) refers exclusively to the spicy condiment.
[src:bay-leaf/ajika] While the name is a Northwest Caucasian loanword, the dish is a defining staple of Mingrelian cuisine.
[src:bay-leaf/ajika] In the Abkhaz language, the condiment is formally known as **apyrpyl-jika** (pepper-salt), whereas the standalone term *ajika* became the standardized name for the specific Mingrelian preparation.
[src:bay-leaf/ajika] This distinction confirms that in the Mingrelian tradition, Ajika is not a synonym for salt, but a unique, processed condiment.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] Ajwain's small, oval, seed-like fruits are pale brown schizocarps, which resemble the seeds of other plants in the family Apiaceae such as caraway, cumin and fennel.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] They have a bitter and pungent taste, with a flavor similar to anise and oregano.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] They smell like thyme because they also contain thymol, but they are more aromatic and less subtle in taste, as well as being somewhat bitter and pungent.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] Even a small number of fruits tend to dominate the flavor of a dish.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] Ajwain grows in dry, barren soil in its indigenous regions of India, Iran, Afghanistan, and parts of northern Africa.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] Gujarat and Rajasthan are regions in India well-known for cultivating ajwain.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] The fruits are rarely eaten raw; they are commonly dry-roasted or fried in ghee (clarified butter).
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] This allows the spice to develop a more subtle and complex aroma.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] It is widely used in the cuisine of the Indian subcontinent, often as part of a chaunk (also called a *tarka*), a mixture of spices – sometimes with a little chopped garlic or onion – fried in oil or clarified butter, which is used to flavor a dish at the end of cooking.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] In Afghanistan, the fruits are sprinkled over bread and biscuits.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] Other applications of ajwain include incorporating the seeds in specific types of breads, such as naans and parathas.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] The seeds can also be used as a mouth freshener when mixed with lemon juice and black pepper and then dried, or can be used as an ingredient in hot tea.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] The seeds are also used in Ethiopian cuisine, where they are called *netch azmud*, "Ethiopian caraway", or "white cumin".
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] Ajwain is used in herbalism practices, such as Ayurveda, in the belief that it can treat various disorders.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] However, there is no good evidence that ajwain is effective as a therapy for treating any disease.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] Pregnant women should avoid ajwain due to potential adverse effects on fetal development.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] In high amounts taken orally, ajwain can result in fatal poisoning.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] People taking nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs or antiplatelet medications are susceptible to adverse effects from ajwain ingestion, as ajwain has anti-clotting activity of its own.
[src:bay-leaf/ajwain] Hydrodistillation of ajwain fruits yields an essential oil consisting primarily of thymol, γ-terpinene, *p*-cymene, and more than 20 trace compounds which are predominantly terpenoids.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] It is popular throughout West Africa, and goes by many names including **apio**, **ogoglo**, **ogogoro** (**Ogog'**), **VC10,** **Kill Me Quick**, **Efie Nipa, Kele, Kumepreko, Anferewoase, Apiatiti, Home Boy, Nana Drobo, One Touch** among others.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] It is also known as sapele water, kparaga, kai-kai, Sun gbalaja, egun inu igo meaning *The Masquerade in the Bottle*, push-me-push-you, and/or crim-kena, sonsé ("do you do it?" in Yoruba language).
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] In the Igbo language it is known as *Akpuru achia*.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Other Nigerian epithets include: *Udi Ogagan*, *Agbagba* Urhobo, as well *OHMS* (Our Home Made Stuff), *Iced Water*, *Push Me, I Push You* and *Craze man in the bottle*.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Ghanaian moonshine is referred to as akpeteshie.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] With British colonization of what became known as the Gold Coast, such local brewing was outlawed in the early 1930s.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Dotse about his life under British colonial rule: "Our contention was that the drink the white man brought is the same as ours.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] The white men's contention was that ours was too strong...Before the white men came we were using akpeteshie.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] But when they came they banned it, probably because they wanted to make sales on their own liquor.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] When you had a visitor whom you knew very well, then you ordered that kpótomenui be brought.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] The name "akpeteshie" was given to the drink with its prohibition: the word comes from the Ga language (*ape te shie*, the act of hiding) spoken in greater Accra and means *they are hiding*, referring to the secretive way in which non-European inhabitants were forced to consume the beverage.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Despite being outlawed, illicit spirits remained commonplace, with reports that even schoolboys were able to easily obtain akpeteshie through the 1930s.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Demand for akpeteshie and the profits to be made from its sale was enough to encourage the spread of sugar cane cultivation in the Anlo region of Ghana.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Distillation was legalized with decolonization and Ghanaian independence.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] The first factory was established in the Volta Region, taking advantage of the area's supply of sugar cane plantations.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Ogogoro is distilled from the juice of Raffia palm trees.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] An incision is made in the trunk and a gourd placed outside it for collection, which is collected a day or two later.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] After extraction, the sap is boiled to form steam, which subsequently condenses and is collected for consumption.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Akpeteshie is distilled from palm wine or sugarcane juice.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] This sweetened liquid or wine is first fermented in a large barrels, sometimes with the help of yeast.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] After this first stage of fermentation, fires are built under the barrels in order to bring the liquid to a boil and pass the resulting vapor through a copper pipe within cooling barrels, where it condenses and drips into sieved jars.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] The boiled juice then undergoes a distillation.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] The resulting spirit is between 40 and 50% alcohol by volume.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Akpeteshie is not professionally bottled or sealed, but instead poured into unlabeled used bottles.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] The spirit can be bought wholesale from a brewer or by the glass at boutiques and bars.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Although not professionally advertised, the drink is very popular.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] This is partially due to its price, which is lower than that of other professionally bottled or imported drinks.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Its relative cheapness makes it a drink associated more with the poor, but even those who can afford better quality are said to consume the spirit in secret.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] The potency of the liquor heavily affects the bodily senses, providing a feeling likened to that of a knockout punch.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Practiced drinkers can be seen acknowledging receipt by blowing out air or pounding their chest.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] As drink and commodity, respectively, ogogoro carries substantial cultural and economic significance within Nigeria.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] It is an essential part of numerous religious and social ceremonies; Burutu (Ijaw) priests pour it onto the ground as offerings to contact their gods, while fathers of Nigerian brides use it as a libation by which they provide their official blessing to a wedding.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] The economic facets of ogogoro have been equally salient throughout recent Nigerian history.
[src:bay-leaf/akpeteshie] Many poor Nigerian families homebrew the drink as a means of economic subsistence, many of whom sell shots of it on city street corners.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Currently, *Allanblackia* seeds are harvested in the wild to produce the oil, but these producers cannot produce enough oil to meet market demand.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Finding sustainable ways to increase production could bring many social, environmental, and economic benefits to the communities which produce *Allanblackia*.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] To ensure increased production is sustainable and benefits the communities growing the trees, a number of organizations have collaborated to develop a set of standards and methods as guidelines for increasing *Allanblackia* production.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Other organizations are working to establish tree nurseries and other sustainable means of domesticating *Allanblackia*.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Allanblackia oil is an edible vegetable oil derived from the seeds from the fruits of *Allanblackia* trees.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] This is an evergreen tree producing big brown fruits.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Inside those fruits are the seeds that contain the allanblackia oil.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] The genus *Allanblackia*, which belongs to the family Clusiaceae, consists of nine (possibly ten) tree species, all restricted to Africa.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] All members of the genus are dioecious (having separate male and female trees).
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] There are nine published species of *Allanblackia*, mostly very similar to each other.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] *Allanblackia* trees are commonly found in the wet tropical rain belt of West, Central and East Africa (from Sierra Leone to Tanzania).
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] They grow primarily in tropical rainforests, but can also be found on cultivated farmland areas.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] These species occur in moist low-land areas (*A. parviflora*, *A. floribunda*) or upland rain forests (*A. stuhlmannii*).
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] The genus *Allanblackia* was named in honour of the botanist Allan Black.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] He was the first curator of Kew Gardens and was responsible for the private collection of Charles Darwin.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Very respected amongst his peers, he died at a young age aboard ship off the Cocos Islands in the Bay of Bengal and the genus *Allanblackia* was named in his memory.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] The name of *Allanblackia* trees used by the indigenous people in Tanzania is actually *msambu* or *mkimbo* in Swahili or sometimes *mkani* (*mkanyi*, *mkany*) in local languages.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] In Nigeria area of River State the local name used is *obiobo obo*.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] A key characteristic is that the fatty acids are organized into a two main triglycerides.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] These are called 1,3-distearoyl-2-oleoyl-glycerol (abbreviated as SOS at an average level of 69%) and 1,2-dioleoyl-3-stearoyl-sn-glycerol (abbreviated as sn-SOO at an average level of 23%).
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] This simple triglyceride composition provides *Allanblackia* seed oil with very steep melting behavior.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] This composition makes it useful for making food products such as margarine, without any further modification like fractionation of fractional crystallization.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Specific physical characteristics of SOS-SOO mixtures, like fat crystallization aspects, have extensively been investigated in model systems.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] The volumes of Allanblackia seeds, and hence seed oil, produced until now very low.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] The volume of allanblackia seed oil is in the range of 100 metric tonnes per annum only.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] These volumes are generated by wild-harvesting mainly done by collectors in Tanzania.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] When initial studies on the potential of wild-harvesting were done in the early 2000s, the expectations were very high predicting annual production of up to 40,000 tonnes of seeds.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] In reality only a few tonnes of seeds were harvested in the first year as the number of wild Allanblackia trees that could actually be harvested had severely been overestimated.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Through the plantation of the tree with local farmers in Tanzania, Ghana and Nigeria, the production volumes are expected to increase in the coming decade, once these trees are old enough to starting producing fruits and big enough to carry more of the large fruit pods.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Increasing the volumes obviously must be done sustainably and hence socio-economic and environmental aspects are being looked at.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] For example, the value of Allanblackia as a new cash (annual) crop for Africa means training of local communities not to cut Allanblackia trees for use as timber and firewood.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] But doing so is also a means of helping to conserve local biodiversity.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] The Union for Ethical Biotrade (UEBT) has developed a standard and a verification framework against which the sustainability of the Allanblackia supply chain can be audited and approved.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] UEBT is a member of the International Social and Environmental Accreditation and Labelling Alliance, which promotes sustainability standards.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Wild harvesting as a production method is limited because there are not enough trees to satisfy demand and Allanblackia's flowering and fruiting behavior is erratic.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Since 2006, Novel Development Tanzania has been involved in a domestication program together with the World Agroforestry Centre to domesticate the species using participatory tree domestication approach.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] The program includes community sensitization, exploration, participatory selections of superior mother trees, conservation in field gene banks, development of agroforestry systems with Allanblackia and market development.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Secondly, the program consists of developing asexual and sexual propagation protocols, which are necessary to overcome challenges in multiplication such as seed dormancy, long juvenile phase and high variability of desired traits.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] The domestication program of Allanblackia through public-private partnership and participatory tree domestication could serve as a model for domestication of other underutilized African tree species of high economic potential.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] In Tanzania the use of allanblackia seed oil goes back almost a century.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] It has been reported that during the First World War allanblackia oil was already tested as a cocoa butter alternative.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Also in the seventies the such application was again explored in Europe.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] However the application never hit the market because larger volumes of the oil were simply not available due to the lack of an organized supply chain.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Nowadays there is still in hardly any local use of Allanblackia seed oil as people prefer use of easily available liquid oils and cheap industrial soaps.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] The allanblackia tree has predominantly been used for timber in the last decades and hence the number of trees has significantly reduced .
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Most of the allanblackia trees nowadays remaining in the wild are growing in the East Usambara Mountains which provides the right climate for this tree.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] As a result, even today the volumes of oil available from wild-harvesting are still very small.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] The major application potential identified today is in the use as a structuring fat to produce low-trans margarines and dairy cream alternatives, and as cocoa butter equivalent in confectionery applications.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] In the European Union as of December 2014, all different types of vegetable oils will be listed on the ingredient label of food products using those ingredients.
[src:bay-leaf/allanblackia-oil] Recently Allanblackia seed oil was introduced in margarine and can be found as such on the product ingredient list.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] The plants which provide alligator pepper are herbaceous, perennial, flowering plants of the ginger family (Zingiberaceae), native to swampy habitats along the West African coast.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] Once the pod is open and the seeds are revealed, the reason for this spice's common English name becomes apparent as the seeds have a papery skin enclosing them and the bumps of the seeds within this skin is reminiscent of an alligator's back.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] As mbongo spice, the seeds of alligator pepper are often sold as the grains isolated from the pod and with the outer skin removed.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] Mbongo spice is most commonly either *A. danielli* or *A. citratum*, and has a more floral aroma than *A. exscapum* (which is the commonest source of the entire pod).
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] It is a common ingredient in West African cuisine, where it imparts both pungency and a spicy aroma to soups and stews.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] Even in West Africa, alligator pepper is an expensive spice, so is used sparingly.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] Often, a single whole pod is pounded in a pestle and mortar before half of it is added (along with black pepper) as a flavouring to West African soups or boiled rice.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] The spice can also be substituted in any recipe using grains of paradise or black cardamom to provide a hotter and more pungent flavour.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] When babies are born in Yoruba culture, they are given a small taste of alligator pepper (atare) shortly after birth as part of the routine baby-welcoming process, and it is also used as an ingredient at traditional meet-and-greets.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] In Igboland, alligator pepper, *ósè ọ́jị́* with kola nuts are used in naming ceremonies, as presentation to visiting guests, and for other social events with the kola nut rite.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] The Igbo present and eat the alligator pepper together with kola nuts.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] In virtually every Igbo ceremony, alligator peppers and kola nuts are presented to guests at the top of the agenda and prior to any other food or entertainment.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] Prayers and libations are made together with kola nuts and alligator pepper.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] In Ibibio, Efik (Akwa Ibom State and Cross River State of Nigeria where it is known as Ntuen Ibok, it has a central part in ceremonies as well as being used for medicinal purposes.
[src:bay-leaf/alligator-pepper] During the COVID-19 pandemic, it was used in medicine.
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] The **bay leaf** is an aromatic leaf commonly used as a herb in cooking.
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] It can be used whole, either dried or fresh, in which case it is removed from the dish before consumption, or less commonly used in ground form.
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] Bay leaves come from various plants and are used for their distinctive flavour and fragrance.
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] The most common source is the bay laurel (*Laurus nobilis*).
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] Other types include California bay laurel (*Umbellularia californica*), Indian bay leaf (*Cinnamomum tamala*), Indonesian bay leaf (*Syzygium polyanthum*), West Indian bay (*Pimenta racemosa*), and Mexican bay leaf (*Litsea glaucescens*).
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] Bay leaves contain essential oils, such as eucalyptol, terpenes, and methyleugenol, which contribute to their taste and aroma.
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] Bay leaves are used in cuisines including Indian, Filipino, European, and Caribbean.
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] They are typically used in soups, stews, meat, seafood, and vegetable dishes.
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] The leaves should be removed from the cooked food before eating as they can be abrasive in the digestive tract.
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] Bay leaves are used as an insect repellent in pantries and as an active ingredient in killing jars for entomology.
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] In Eastern Orthodoxy liturgy, they are used to symbolize Jesus' destruction of Hades and freeing of the dead.
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] While some visually similar plants have poisonous leaves, bay leaves are not toxic.
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] However, they remain stiff even after cooking and may pose a choking hazard or cause harm to the digestive tract if swallowed whole or in large pieces.
[src:bay-leaf/bay-leaf] Canadian food and drug regulations set specific standards for bay leaves, including limits on ash content, moisture levels, and essential oil content.
